Actually starting below zero could be misleading if negative values shown but no negative cases. Including negative space may exaggerate differences? If axis starts at -1K, then the peak at 3K appears larger relative to zero baseline? Starting below zero inflates visual height? Actually typical line chart of cases would start at zero; showing negative values creates extra space making peaks look less steep? Might minimize perception? Also the claim that third wave comparable to first wave: chart up to March 2021, third wave "currently rising" approaching first peak. Could be cherry-picking because only showing up to March 2021; maybe later it declines. But within given period, it's okay.

Potential errors: Truncated axis (not starting at zero) - axis starts at -1K, not zero. That's a truncation. Also Unclear encoding? Not really. Negative values artifact may be considered misleading.

Also could be cherry-picking if they only show certain time window to make third wave appear comparable, but they show entire year March 2020 to March 2021, which includes all three waves. So not cherry-picking.

The caption says third wave comparable in magnitude to first wave. The chart shows third wave "approaching" but not yet equal; might be inference ahead of data; could be causal inference? Not really.

Thus main misleading aspect: Truncated axis (starting below zero). Also maybe "Incorrect reading of chart" if they claim equality but not yet reached, but they say "approaching" which is okay.

Is it intentional? Likely unintentional design artifact; not deliberately to mislead. So is_intentional false with moderate confidence.

Rhetoric types: Information Access Rhetoric (choice of timeframe, includes all three waves). Could be present. Mapping Rhetoric (position mapping of cases). Linguistic-Based Rhetoric (caption claims). Provenance Rhetoric likely absent (no source). Procedural Rhetoric likely absent.

Now assign confidence levels: is_misleading: true (due to truncated axis). Confidence maybe 80.

Intentional: false with confidence 70.
